      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "It's more accurate to say that the \"good\" version of nationalism is aspirational, while the \"bad\" version is empirically proven when it becomes toxic. The concept of \"social cohesion\" is often a rhetorical tool, but its successful manifestation requires a commitment to universal human rights, not just ethnic homogeneity. History provides overwhelming evidence that when nationalism becomes an end in itself, its exclusionary nature inevitably leads to friction and conflict.",
